      <div class="description">
        <p>
          Synesthesia is a neurological phenomenon in which one
          sense is perceived simultaneously with one or more additional senses.
          For example, objects like letters, shapes, numbers, or even people's names
          are perceived at the same time as sensory perceptions such as smell, color,
          or flavor, resulting in interesting combinations of perceptions!
        </p>
        <p>
          So how might a synesthete who sees each letter as a different color—a
          form called "grapheme-color synesthesia"—see the world?
          This tool's purpose is to explore that possibility.
        </p>
        <p>
          Simply type in any text, such as your name, a song lyric, or a quote
          into the text box below. Click the "VISUALIZE" button to see your text
          visually represented as colors. Note that each letter corresponds to a
          different color. How might different types of text, like songs, palindromes,
          or even genetic code, generate interesting color patterns? Try it out below:
        </p>
      </div>
